ked countries]]\n[[Category:Member states of the Union of South American Nations]]\n[[Category:Republics]]\n[[Category:Countries in South America]]\n[[Category:Spanish-speaking countries and territories]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1825]]\n[[Category:Member states of the United Nations]]\n", "name_user": "2601:642:c481:4640:6c95:4a22:993f:3118", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(fixed that shit for ya)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bolivia"}
{"title_page": "Modern Artillery", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Modern Artillery\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[The Living End]]\n| cover      = The_Living_End-MODERN_ARTillery.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 28 October 2003 (International) <br> 2 March 2004 (USA)\n| recorded   = 2003\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Ocean Studios]] ([[Burbank, California|Burbank, CA]]) \n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Punk rock]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n* [[electronic rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 49:43\n| label      = {{hlist|[[EMI]] (2003)|[[Reprise Records|Reprise]] (2004)}}\n| producer   = [[Mark Trombino]]\n| prev_title = [[Roll On (The Living End album)|Roll On]]\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[From Here on In (The Living End album)|From Here on In]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n'''''Modern Artillery''''' (stylized as '''''MODERN ARTillery''''') is the third studio album by Australian [[punk rock]] band [[The Living End]], released on 28 October 2003 internationally and on 2 March 2004 in the United States. It is the first album to feature drummer [[Andy Strachan]], since [[Travis Demsey]] had left the band after their second album, ''[[Roll On (The Living End album)|Roll On]]''.\n\nThe song \"[[Who's Gonna Save Us?]]\" was released as a [[Single (music)|single]] and appeared in commercials for the documentary film ''[[Fahrenheit 9/11]]''. \"End of the World\" is featured on the soundtrack for the video game ''[[Tony Hawk's Underground 2]]''.\n\n[[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]] publicised that the album had officially achieved platinum status in Australia in November 2007.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = 49:43\n| headline =\n| all_writing = [[Chris Cheney]], except where noted\n| title1 = What Would You Do?\n| note1 = <small>[[Scott Owen]]</small>\n| length1 = 1:28\n| title2 = [[One Said to the Other]]\n| note2 =\n| length2 = 2:46\n| title3 = [[Who's Gonna Save Us?]]\n| note3 =\n| length3 = 3:21\n| title4 = End of the World\n| note4 = \n| length4 = 3:36\n| title5 = Jimmy\n| length5 = 3:29\n| title6 = [[Tabloid Magazine (song)|Tabloid Magazine]]\n| note6 = \n| length6 = 3:21\n| title7 = In the End\n| note7 = \n| length7 = 4:16\n| title8 = Maitland Street\n| note8 = \n| length8 = 4:07\n| title9 = Putting You Down\n| note9 = \n| length9 = 3:47\n| title10 = Short Notice\n| note10 = <small>Scott Owen, [[Chris Cheney]], [[Andy Strachan]]</small>\n| length10 = 2:43\n| title11 = So What?\n| note11 =\n| length11 = 2:58\n| title12 = Rising Up from the Ashes\n| note12 =\n| length12 = 3:16\n| title13 = Hold Up\n| note13 =\n| length13 = 2:28\n| title14 = The Room\n| note14 =\n| length14 = 8:07\n}}\n*In the [[Phonograph record|vinyl]] releases of the album, the tracks ''One Said to the Other'' and ''Tabloid Magazine'' are swapped.<ref>https://coretexrecords.com/Living-End-The-modern-artillery</ref><ref>https://www.jpc.de/jpcng/poprock/detail/-/art/the-living-end-modern-artillery/hnum/9648577</ref>\n\n===Bonus DVD===\nReleased as a limited edition bonus DVD with the Australian version of the album, it includes six live tracks from ''[[Splendour in the Grass]]'' 2003, as well as backstage footage. All tracks were recorded live at Splendour in the Grass, [[Byron Bay, New South Wales|Byron Bay]], Australia.\n\n#\"[[Roll On (The Living End song)|Roll On]]\"\n#\"[[Save the Day]]\"\n#\"Carry Me Home\"\n#\"[[West End Riot]]\"\n#\"E-Boogie\"\n#\"[[Second Solution / Prisoner of Society|Second Solution]]\"\n\n==Singles==\n*\"[[One Said to the Other]]\" (2003) <small>\u2013 #19 Australia, [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2002]] #52</small>\n*\"[[Who's Gonna Save Us?]]\" (2003) <small>\u2013 #37 Australia, [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2003]] #23</small>\n*\"[[Tabloid Magazine (song)|Tabloid Magazine]]\" (2003) <small>\u2013 Triple J Hottest 100, 2003 #66</small>\n\n==Personnel==\n===The Living End===\n*[[Chris Cheney]] \u2013 vocals, guitar\n*[[Scott Owen]] \u2013 double bass, vocals\n*[[Andy Strachan]] \u2013 drums\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2003)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|Australia|3|album=MODERN ARTILLERY|artist=The Living End|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 October 2019|refname=\"ARIA Albums Chart\"}}\n|-\n{{album chart|New Zealand|43|album=MODERN ARTILLERY|artist=The Living End|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 October 2019|refname=\"NZ Albums Chart\"}}\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Australia|artist=The Living End|title=Modern Artillery|award=Platinum|certyear=2007|refname=\"Album Certification\"|access-date=4 October 2019}}\n{{certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{The Living End}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Modern Artillery}}\n[[Category:The Living End albums]]\n[[Category:2003 albums]]\n[[Category:2004 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Mark Trombino]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Modern Artillery\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[The Living End]]\n| cover      = The_Living_End-MODERN_ARTillery.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 28 October 2003 (International) <br> 2 March 2004 (USA)\n| recorded   = 2003\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Ocean Studios]] ([[Burbank, California|Burbank, CA]]) \n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Punk rock]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n* [[electronic rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 49:43\n| label      = {{hlist|[[EMI]] (2003)|[[Reprise Records|Reprise]] (2004)}}\n| producer   = [[Mark Trombino]]\n| prev_title = [[Roll On (The Living End album)|Roll On]]\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[From Here on In (The Living End album)|From Here on In]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n'''''Modern Artillery''''' (stylized as '''''MODERN ARTillery''''') is the third studio album by Australian [[punk rock]] band [[The Living End]], released on 28 October 2003 internationally and on 2 March 2004 in the United States. It is the first album to feature drummer [[Andy Strachan]], since [[Travis Demsey]] had left the band after their second album, ''[[Roll On (The Living End album)|Roll On]]''.\n\nThe song \"[[Who's Gonna Save Us?]]\" was released as a [[Single (music)|single]] and appeared in commercials for the documentary film ''[[Fahrenheit 9/11]]''. \"End of the World\" is featured on the soundtrack for the video game ''[[Tony Hawk's Underground 2]]''.\n\n[[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]] publicised that the album had officially achieved platinum status in Australia in November 2007.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = 49:43\n| headline =\n| all_writing = [[Chris Cheney]], except where noted\n| title1 = What Would You Do?\n| note1 = [[Scott Owen]]\n| length1 = 1:28\n| title2 = [[One Said to the Other]]\n| note2 =\n| length2 = 2:46\n| title3 = [[Who's Gonna Save Us?]]\n| note3 =\n| length3 = 3:21\n| title4 = End of the World\n| note4 = \n| length4 = 3:36\n| title5 = Jimmy\n| length5 = 3:29\n| title6 = [[Tabloid Magazine (song)|Tabloid Magazine]]\n| note6 = \n| length6 = 3:21\n| title7 = In the End\n| note7 = \n| length7 = 4:16\n| title8 = Maitland Street\n| note8 = \n| length8 = 4:07\n| title9 = Putting You Down\n| note9 = \n| length9 = 3:47\n| title10 = Short Notice\n| note10 = Scott Owen, [[Chris Cheney]], [[Andy Strachan]]\n| length10 = 2:43\n| title11 = So What?\n| note11 =\n| length11 = 2:58\n| title12 = Rising Up from the Ashes\n| note12 =\n| length12 = 3:16\n| title13 = Hold Up\n| note13 =\n| length13 = 2:28\n| title14 = The Room\n| note14 =\n| length14 = 8:07\n}}\n*In the [[Phonograph record|vinyl]] releases of the album, the tracks ''One Said to the Other'' and ''Tabloid Magazine'' are swapped.<ref>https://coretexrecords.com/Living-End-The-modern-artillery</ref><ref>https://www.jpc.de/jpcng/poprock/detail/-/art/the-living-end-modern-artillery/hnum/9648577</ref>\n\n===Bonus DVD===\nReleased as a limited edition bonus DVD with the Australian version of the album, it includes six live tracks from ''[[Splendour in the Grass]]'' 2003, as well as backstage footage. All tracks were recorded live at Splendour in the Grass, [[Byron Bay, New South Wales|Byron Bay]], Australia.\n\n#\"[[Roll On (The Living End song)|Roll On]]\"\n#\"[[Save the Day]]\"\n#\"Carry Me Home\"\n#\"[[West End Riot]]\"\n#\"E-Boogie\"\n#\"[[Second Solution / Prisoner of Society|Second Solution]]\"\n\n==Singles==\n*\"[[One Said to the Other]]\" (2003) <small>\u2013 #19 Australia, [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2002]] #52</small>\n*\"[[Who's Gonna Save Us?]]\" (2003) <small>\u2013 #37 Australia, [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2003]] #23</small>\n*\"[[Tabloid Magazine (song)|Tabloid Magazine]]\" (2003) <small>\u2013 Triple J Hottest 100, 2003 #66</small>\n\n==Personnel==\n===The Living End===\n*[[Chris Cheney]] \u2013 vocals, guitar\n*[[Scott Owen]] \u2013 double bass, vocals\n*[[Andy Strachan]] \u2013 drums\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2003)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|Australia|3|album=MODERN ARTILLERY|artist=The Living End|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 October 2019|refname=\"ARIA Albums Chart\"}}\n|-\n{{album chart|New Zealand|43|album=MODERN ARTILLERY|artist=The Living End|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 October 2019|refname=\"NZ Albums Chart\"}}\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Australia|artist=The Living End|title=Modern Artillery|award=Platinum|certyear=2007|refname=\"Album Certification\"|access-date=4 October 2019}}\n{{certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{The Living End}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Modern Artillery}}\n[[Category:The Living End albums]]\n[[Category:2003 albums]]\n[[Category:2004 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Mark Trombino]]\n", "name_user": "Machr123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrack listing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modern_Artillery"}
